## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2015 Premera Blue Cross data breach** — a healthcare insurance company that was breached in a cyberattack affecting nearly 11 million people. The attackers gained access through a spear-phishing email and maintained access to the network for almost nine months before the breach was detected.

What stood out to me from a risk treatment perspective was the post-incident investigation findings. Auditors found that Premera had received a federal audit report identifying significant security vulnerabilities two weeks before the breach began. The recommended remediations had not been implemented. In risk treatment terms, the organization had identified the risks — and then implicitly accepted them without documentation, without authority, and without a plan to revisit them.

The distinction between conscious, documented risk acceptance and passive risk neglect is one of the most important practical concepts in risk management. Premera paid a $74 million settlement — the largest HIPAA settlement at the time — and faced significant regulatory scrutiny. The financial cost of that implicit "acceptance" dwarfed what mitigation would have cost.

That example reinforced something I want to carry through this entire project: risk decisions need to be explicit, documented, and owned by someone with appropriate authority. Anything less is not a risk treatment strategy — it is just hope.

